[1] Pakistan (Karachi)
Date: Mon 8 Oct 2007
Source: The Post [edited]
<http://thepost.com.pk/NatNewsT.aspx?dtlid=122222&catid=2>

The number of dengue fever patients is steadily increasing in the city,
with the total number of patients registered at 601, including 590
admissions and 11 outpatients, on Saturday [6 Oct 2007] since August this
year [2007].
Dr Shakil Malik, additional health secretary and oordinator, Dengue Fever
Monitoring Cell of Sindh Health Department, told Associated Press of
Pakistan on Saturday [6 Oct 2007] that 98 dengue fever patients are
currently hospitalized in different health care facilities of Karachi.
The data made available to media was said to be based on daily reports from
10 - 13 different hospitals of Karachi. "As per available data, 272 of the
601 dengue cases were positive, 206 negative and 126 cases are yet to be
confirmed," the monitoring cell coordinator said. He appealed to all
hospital administrators as well as general physicians to support the Cell
in data compilation.
"This will ultimately help the public, as we would be able to chalk-out an
effective preventive strategy in accordance to serotypes of the ailment
identified among each of the patients," he said.
Dr Shakil in this regard also appealed to all the medical facilities to
apprise the cell of the exact nature of dengue cases being brought to them
and also the associated deaths. He acknowledged confusion with regard to
deaths reported by the media and mentioned that there had been an instance
when a man, fully recovered from dengue fever, died of a heart attack but
was claimed to be a victim of dengue.
It is through media we come to know of cases and dengue induced deaths, but
these are never officially reported to us, thus creating distress among the
masses. "The disease is there, but the fact also remains that it is
preventable, and each of us in our individual capacities has to protect
ourselves against it," the additional health secretary said.
To a query regarding instances of malaria, he said cases of both
falciparium malaria and vivax malaria were reported during the recent past,
and that the health department has a strategy in place and measures
strictly adopted to contain and prevent these cases. He said that while
malaria-causing mosquitoes flourish in stagnant filthy water, the _Aedes
aegypti_ mosquitoes breed in clean water stored in uncovered tanks,
buckets, utensils, flower vases etc.
"We can definitely get rid of the ailments through concerted efforts on
part of government, civic agencies and citizens in their individual
capacities," he commented. He advised people to ensure spraying
insecticides or even discarded motor oil on pools and puddles of water so
that a screen is created preventing breeding of mosquitoes.
Application of mosquito repellent oil, coils, use of mosquito nets, hygiene
and cleanliness, ensuring that all parts of the body are duly covered to
avoid mosquito bites and timely referral to doctors in case of persistent
fever and cold were also strongly advised by the health department official.
--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
[This report is somewhat confusing. This article indicates that there were
601 registered dengue cases reported, although 206 of these were listed as
negative. So it is not clear if these 206 were dengue cases or not.
Although it is useful to know which dengue virus serotypes are circulating
in the population, it is not necessary to have this information in hand
before mounting a vector mosquito control effort. Elimination of water
catchments to prevent aedes mosquito breeding is the same irrespective of
the dengue viruses being transmitted. Insecticide fumigation of adult
mosquitoes may also provide temporary reduction of virus transmission, but
unless breeding sites are eliminated, the epidemic is likely to continue as
new adults are recruited into the vector population. Where aedes mosquitoes
are breeding in drinking water storage containers, motor oil application
should not be used.
Karachi is located on the Arabian Sea. A map of Pakistan can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/pakistan_pol_2002.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]
