[2] Philippines
Date: Thu 4 Oct 2007
Source: Sun Star [edited]
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/ceb/2007/10/04/news/after.4.000.dengue.cases.in.just.one.week.with.cebu.city.listing.1.000th.victim.this.year.html>

The government has issued a nationwide dengue fever alert after recording
more than 4000 cases in the 2nd week of September [2007], the health
department said yesterday [3 Oct 2007]. It had recorded 24 689 cases of the
mosquitoborne disease in all since January [2007], with 283 deaths.
The head of the National Epidemiology Center, Eric Tayag, said in the
statement that he expected a sharp increase in the number of cases in
September and October 2007: "It's during this period that we expect the
disease to proliferate due to the wet weather," he said.
In Cebu City, regional and city health officials warned the Cebu City
Council that the worst is yet to come after the city recorded its 1000th
dengue case.
As of 30 Sep [2007], 73 of Cebu City's 80 barangays have already been
affected by the dengue virus, infecting a total of 1000 individuals, mostly
children aged 6-10 years old. There have been 25 deaths recorded in Cebu
City from 1 Jan to 30 Sep [2007].
Central Visayas also saw an increase of 214 dengue cases in just one week.
The number of cases is 48 per cent higher than the same period last year
[2006].
Cebu City has the largest number of dengue cases in the region. The city
has been declared a hotspot, particularly in Barangays Pardo and Bulacao.
The total number of dengue cases from 1 Jan to 29 Sep this year [2007]
reached 3420 cases, according to the Regional Epidemiology and Surveillance
Unit (Resu) 7 of the Department of Health (DOH).
The previous Resu report was for 22 Sep [2007], with 3216 cases.
In the same period last year [2006], there were only 2316 cases, or 48.1
per cent fewer. There were also 86 deaths in the region this year compared
with last year's 51.
Cebu City officials will meet later this week to come up with plans on the
most efficient way to fight dengue, especially after families reportedly
spent at least P30 million [USD 673 733] to treat the 1000 patients.
During the council session yesterday [3 Oct 2007], Vice Mayor Michael Rama
said he was surprised to learn about the number of dengue cases in the
city, which make up 34.2 per cent of the 3216 cases recorded in Central
Visayas as of 22 Sep [2007]. Rama is worried that the increasing number of
dengue cases could turn off tourists from coming to the region, considered
the country's tourism hub.
Dr Jonathan Neil Erasmo, DOH 7 dengue program coordinator, and City Health
Department Chief Fe Cabugao urged the councilors to pass measures that will
help in the dengue prevention campaign, such as intensifying the waste
segregation and other sanitation programs as a way of eliminating the
breeding sites of mosquitoes.
Cabugao also said that contrary to what the councilors are hoping, Cebu
City cannot be dengue virus-free since it is already endemic to the city,
which means dengue cases will arise throughout the year.
The health officials also urged the public to implement the 4-S in the
campaign against dengue: search and destroy breeding sites of mosquitoes,
seek immediate consultation, self protection and saying "no" to
indiscriminate fogging unless there is a dengue outbreak in the area.
