[3] Micronesia (Yap)
Date: Sat 6 Oct 2007
Source: Pacific Daily News [edited]
<http://www.guampdn.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071006/NEWS01/710060311/1002>

An outbreak of a deadly mosquitoborne virus in Yap has prompted local
health officials to be on the lookout for the possible transmission of the
disease to the island.
At least 6 cases of the dengue fever virus in Yap have been confirmed --
including one fatal case -- since the samples were tested late last month
[September 2007], according to a release from the Guam Department of Public
Health and Social Services.
With the rainy season in full swing and the routine transit of people to
and from Yap, Public Health is pushing forward with its campaign to prevent
the disease from occurring on the island, said Rosanna Rabago, an
environmental health specialist supervisor with the Bureau of Animal and
Vector Control. The island has had just one case of dengue fever reported
so far this year [2007]. The individual contracted the disease while in the
Philippines, Rabago said. The preventive measures also are in response to
the warning from the World Health Organization that an outbreak of dengue
in the Western Pacific would be likely in the upcoming years.
The outbreak also comes at a time when Yap continues to battle the Zika
virus, which is similar to dengue but with milder symptoms. Public Health
also has kept watch for that mosquitoborne disease on Guam, Rebago said.
"Guam, by far, has been very lucky," Rabago said. "We're fortunate that we
have not had to worry about any of these diseases establishing on the
island, and we hope that remains the case. We need to be vigilant and
continue to increase public awareness and education in regards to
mosquitoborne disease education."
Mosquitoes breed in areas with standing water, a major concern for Public
Health since it has continued to rain on the island over the last few
months, she said. "People need to be aware that even the smallest container
that holds water can have the potential to be a mosquito breeding site,"
Rebago said. "It's just more prevalent during the rainy season."
[byline: Lacee AC Martinez]
