[5] Dominican Republic
Date: Thu 4 Oct 2007
Source: La Republica [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.listindiario.com.do/app/article.aspx?id=31437>

Dozens of children and adolescents ill from dengue are interned in public
and private medical centers in this city, which, in the past 3 weeks, has
caused great absenteeism from schools.
Just in the Nuestra Senora de Regla hospital, 10 infants were admitted with
classic dengue fever, 3 were released and one was referred to the Robert
Reid Cabra Children's Hopital in Santo Domingo.
The disease is mainly attacking the childhood population 2-14 years of age.
Although the illness preferentially attacks the population in poor
neighborhoods, this time the outbreak extends to sectors [of the city] of
the middle class, such as Las Marias and Riviera del Sur.
The children hospitalized in the pediatric isolation unit of the hospital
are between 2 and 13 years of age and come from the Villa Majega, Santa
Cruz, Pueblo Nuevo y Santa Elena neighborhoods, while others come from
rural areas such as Galion, Matanzas, Sombrero and others.
The epidemiologist of the Provincial Health Directorate, Dr Agustina
Martinez, said that the number of cases has increased considerably, "it
seems that new [dengue] cases are appearing in children who are infected
[with dengue virus] for the 1st time." She said that the situation is most
serious in those areas where potable water is not available so that the
neighbors necessarily have to store water, and these storage sites become
permanent [mosquito] breeding areas.
Both Drs Tolentino and Fremio Casado, the pediatrician in charge of the
pediatric unit of the Nuestra Senora de Regla hospital, agreed in signaling
that dengue is everyone's problem, affirming that, "the population has to
cooperate in the elimination of the [mosquito] breeding sites in their
[household] patios and other places [since ] the [government] authorities
do not have the capability to go to all homes and sites of mosquito
breeding at the same time."
[byline: Jose Dicen]
--
communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>
[The situation in the poor neighborhoods without piped water illustrates
the need to store water in and around homes which, in turn, provides
breeding sites for aedes mosquito vectors. Public education and cooperation
are essential to reduce vector populations and halt dengue virus transmission.
A zoomable map of the Dominican Republic showing the location of Bani can
be accessed at <http://www.maplandia.com/dominican-republic/peravia/bani/>.
